<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Informal_sector&amp;action=edit&amp;section=14" title="Edit section: External links">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="External_links">External links</span></h2>
<ul>
<li><span class="citation Journal">Enrique Ghersi (1997). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.cato.org/pubs/journal/cj17n1/cj17n1-8.pdf">"The Informal Economy in Latin America"</a> (PDF). <i>Cato Journal</i> (<a href="/wiki/Cato_Institute" title="Cato Institute">Cato Institute</a>) <b>17</b> (1)<span class="printonly">. <a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="http://www.cato.org/pubs/journal/cj17n1/cj17n1-8.pdf">http://www.cato.org/pubs/journal/cj17n1/cj17n1-8.pdf</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved 2006-12-18</span>.</span><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=The+Informal+Economy+in+Latin+America&amp;rft.jtitle=Cato+Journal&amp;rft.aulast=Enrique+Ghersi&amp;rft.au=Enrique+Ghersi&amp;rft.date=1997&amp;rft.volume=17&amp;rft.issue=1&amp;rft.pub=%5B%5BCato+Institute%5D%5D&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.cato.org%2Fpubs%2Fjournal%2Fcj17n1%2Fcj17n1-8.pdf&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Informal_sector"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span> An article by a collaborator of de Soto.</li>
<li><span class="citation web"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.undp.org/legalempowerment">"The Commission on Legal Empowerment of the Poor"</a>. United Nations Development Program<span class="printonly">. <a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="http://www.undp.org/legalempowerment">http://www.undp.org/legalempowerment</a></span>.</span><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=The+Commission+on+Legal+Empowerment+of+the+Poor&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft.pub=United+Nations+Development+Program&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.undp.org%2Flegalempowerment&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Informal_sector"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span> Co-chaired by de Soto and former secretary of state <a href="/wiki/Madeleine_Albright" title="Madeleine Albright">Madeleine Albright</a>.</li>
<li><span class="citation web">John C. Cross (January, 1995). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://web.archive.org/web/20061213200213/http://www.openair.org/cross/vendnow2.html">"Formalizing the informal economy: The Case of Street Vendors in Mexico City"</a>. Archived from <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.openair.org/cross/vendnow2.html">the original</a> on 2006-12-13<span class="printonly">. <a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="http://web.archive.org/web/20061213200213/http://www.openair.org/cross/vendnow2.html">http://web.archive.org/web/20061213200213/http://www.openair.org/cross/vendnow2.html</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved 2006-12-18</span>.</span><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Formalizing+the+informal+economy%3A+The+Case+of+Street+Vendors+in+Mexico+City&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft.aulast=John+C.+Cross&amp;rft.au=John+C.+Cross&amp;rft.date=January%2C+1995&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fweb.archive.org%2Fweb%2F20061213200213%2Fhttp%3A%2F%2Fwww.openair.org%2Fcross%2Fvendnow2.html&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Informal_sector"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span> A working paper describing attempts to formalize street vending in Mexico.</li>
<li><span class="citation book">World Institute for Development Economics Research (September 17–18, 2004). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.wider.unu.edu/conference/conference-2004-2/conference2004-2.htm"><i>Unlocking Human Potential</i></a>. United Nations University<span class="printonly">. <a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="http://www.wider.unu.edu/conference/conference-2004-2/conference2004-2.htm">http://www.wider.unu.edu/conference/conference-2004-2/conference2004-2.htm</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved 2006-12-18</span>.</span><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Unlocking+Human+Potential&amp;rft.aulast=World+Institute+for+Development+Economics+Research&amp;rft.au=World+Institute+for+Development+Economics+Research&amp;rft.date=September+17%26ndash%3B18%2C+2004&amp;rft.pub=United+Nations+University&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.wider.unu.edu%2Fconference%2Fconference-2004-2%2Fconference2004-2.htm&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Informal_sector"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li><span class="citation Journal">Douglas Uzzell (November 22, 2004). "A Homegrown Mass Transit System in Lima, Peru: A Case of Generative Planning". <i>City &amp; Society</i> <b>1</b> (1): 6–34. <a href="/wiki/Digital_object_identifier" title="Digital object identifier">DOI</a>:<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://dx.doi.org/10.1525%2Fcity.1987.1.1.6">10.1525/city.1987.1.1.6</a>.</span><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=A+Homegrown+Mass+Transit+System+in+Lima%2C+Peru%3A+A+Case+of+Generative+Planning&amp;rft.jtitle=City+%26+Society&amp;rft.aulast=Douglas+Uzzell&amp;rft.au=Douglas+Uzzell&amp;rft.date=November+22%2C+2004&amp;rft.volume=1&amp;rft.issue=1&amp;rft.pages=6%E2%80%9334&amp;rft_id=info:doi/10.1525%2Fcity.1987.1.1.6&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Informal_sector"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.community-links.org/our-national-work/publications/self-employed-people-in-the-informal-economy/">Cheats or Contributors? Self Employed People in the Informal Economy</a> A report by east London Charity <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.community-links.org">Community Links</a> and Microfinance organisation Street UK providing analysis of the motivations of informal workers.</li>
<li><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.community-links.org/ourwork/IENeedNotGreed_page165.aspx">Need not Greed - People in low-paid informal work</a> A report by east London Charity <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.community-links.org">Community Links</a> explores the experience of people on low incomes, doing informal paid work.</li>
<li>World Bank policy note on <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://rru.worldbank.org/PublicPolicyJournal/Summary.aspx?id=301">The Informality Trap: Tax Evasion, Finance, and Productivity in Brazil</a></li>
<li>World Bank policy note on <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://rru.worldbank.org/PublicPolicyJournal/Summary.aspx?id=298">Rising Informality - Reversing the Tide</a></li>
<li><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://rru.worldbank.org/Documents/PapersLinks/informal_economy.pdf">Paper</a> estimating the size of the informal economy in 110 developing, transition and developed countries</li>
<li><span class="citation book">Keith Hart (2000). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.thememorybank.co.uk"><i>The Memory Bank</i></a>. Profile Books<span class="printonly">. <a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="http://www.thememorybank.co.uk">http://www.thememorybank.co.uk</a></span>.</span><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Memory+Bank&amp;rft.aulast=Keith+Hart&amp;rft.au=Keith+Hart&amp;rft.date=2000&amp;rft.pub=Profile+Books&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.thememorybank.co.uk&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Informal_sector"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span> The link is to an online archive of Keith Hart's works.</li>
<li><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.ipsnews.net/new_focus/decent_work/index.asp">The Americas: Decent work - a rarity</a> Independent news reports and features about the world of labour in the Americas by IPS Inter Press Service</li>
